        <h1> The Responsible Cat Owner's Checklist For Taking Care Of A Cat</h1>
        <main>
            <div class="image-container">
                <img src="../images/cats.jpg" alt="Cats" height = "300">
            </div>
            <section class="care-section">
                <ol class="care-list">
                    <li>
                        <h2>Feeding</h2>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Provide high-quality, brand-name cat food.</li>
                            <li>Ensure the diet includes taurine for heart and eye health.</li>
                            <li>Fresh, clean water should be available at all times.</li>
                            <li>Treats should not exceed 5-10% of the diet.</li>
                            <li>Consult your vet if signs of anorexia, diarrhea, vomiting, or lethargy persist.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <h2>Grooming</h2>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Brush or comb your cat regularly to keep the coat clean and reduce shedding and hairballs.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <h2>Handling</h2>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Pick up your cat by placing one hand behind the front legs and another under the hindquarters. Do not lift by the scruff or front legs.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <h2>Housing</h2>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Provide a clean, dry, and comfortable place for your cat to sleep indoors. Outdoor cats face more risks and have shorter lifespans.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <h2>Identification</h2>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Use a safety collar with an ID tag, and consider microchipping your cat.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <h2>Litter Box</h2>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Place the litter box in a quiet, accessible location. Clean it daily and wash it weekly. If your cat refuses to use the litter box, consult a vet.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <h2>Scratching</h2>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Provide a sturdy scratching post to help keep your catâ€™s claws in good condition and protect your furniture.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <h2>Health</h2>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Schedule annual vet visits and vaccinations. Seek immediate veterinary care if your cat is sick or injured.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <h2>Medicines and Poisons</h2>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Only give medications prescribed by a vet. Contact a vet or the ASPCA Animal Poison Control Center if you suspect poisoning.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <h2>Spaying and Neutering</h2>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Spay or neuter your cat by five months of age to prevent unwanted litters and health issues.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                </ol>

